The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Monday, June 07, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Sleuths of the enforcement branch (EB) seized 14,000 video compact discs (VCDs) and a sizeable number of inlay cards from a video library on S.N. Roy Road, in Behala, on Saturday. Deputy superintendent of police (EB) R.K. Adhikari said on Sunday that the shop was run by Gobindalal Shaw and his son. Acting on a tip-off, his sleuths raided the shop and managed to arrest Shaw, but his son gave them the slip. The duplicator used to make the forged VCDs has been seized. 																																																		Residents of Balitikuri, in Howrahs Dasnagar, blocked Howrah-Amta Road on Sunday afternoon for 30 minutes after a Domjur-bound private bus knocked down two youths on a motorcycle. The mishap occurred near Dasnagar railway station. The duo has been admitted to Howrah District Hospital in a serious condition. The bus has been impounded. 																																																		A 40-year-old man was knocked down and killed by a truck on Strand Road on Saturday night. He was taken to SSKM Hospital, where he was declared dead. The driver fled the spot, but his vehicle has been impounded.																																																		Two men were arrested in connection with the unnatural death of a 32-year-old housewife, Jhuma Panja, on Saturday, in Shyampukurs Gokul Mitra Lane. Police said on Sunday that they had rounded up Jhumas husband Santanu and father-in-law Balai for their alleged role in the death.																																																		The Science Association of Bengal released a book, Prithibi Tumi Kemon Achho, on World Environment Day. 							TO Jadavpur Byabasayee Samity for distributing free textbooks to 470 needy schoolchildren
